name: Ragnar Trail Kentuckiana - KY
intro: Ragnar Trail Kentuckiana-KY presented by Salomon was created for those with an adventurous spirit. Your team of 8 (or 4) will come together in early April to conquer a series of three single track trails that start and finish at Ragnar Village. The overnight trail running relay starts on Friday at Otter Creek Outdoor Recreation Area, a hidden gem located close to Fort Knox, and outside of the city lights of Louisville. You'll earn your views of the Ohio River and see clear into Indiana at this uniquely situated location. The green, yellow, and red loops meander through thick green forests and twist along clear creeks. This venue features the perfect mix of technical rocky and rooted surfaces and trails covered with soft, forgiving pine needles. Your legs might burn like a shot of Bourbon, but back at Ragnar Village a celebration will light up the night under a bed of stars where you can enjoy campfires, s'mores, movies, and new friends.

village:
Ragnar Village is the heart and soul of the event. Each trail begins and ends in Ragnar Village. It is the start line, the finish line, and the exchange point. After each loop you will return to the support of your teammates and the adulation of the teams around you. Ragnar Village will be complete with:

  • Bonfire
  • S'mores
  • Food & snacks (Friday night dinner included for each runner)
  • Billions of stars
  • Friday night movie

Training by Salomon

At Salomon our goal is to inspire runners to go beyond the pavement and enjoy greater freedom to run anywhere. We believe that with some tips and training almost anyone can become a trail runner and run the Ragnar Trail Relay. We are here to guide you on your training journey as you prepare to run the Ragnar Trail Relay.

charity:
YMCA Camp Piomingo is the resident summer camp living out the mission of  the Greater Louisville YMCA, which is to put Christian principals into practice through programs that build health, spirit, mind, and body for all. Camp Piomingo offers children from across the United States (and Internationally) the opportunity to experience nature, meet new friends and make lifelong memories — all in a safe, caring, friendly environment. Piomingo campers participate in all kinds of exciting outdoor activities that teach leadership, teamwork and the importance of developing healthy habits, while instilling the Y core values (caring, honesty, respect, and responsibility) that build confidence and character. YMCA Camp Piomingo is nestled in Otter Creek Recreational Park in Brandenburg, Kentucky and serves campers between the ages of 7 and 16 years old. Each summer we inspire creativity, promote passion, and challenge our campers to seek the adventure in all of them!

meta_description: Ragnar Trail Kentuckiana-KY presented by Salomon was created for those with an adventurous spirit. Your team of 8 (or 4) will come together in early April to conquer a series of three single track trails that start and finish at Ragnar Village. The overnight trail running relay starts on Friday at Otter Creek Outdoor Recreation Area, a hidden gem located close to Fort Knox, and outside of the city lights of Louisville.

legs.name: Green Loop - Valley Overlook Trail
legs.description: The Green Loop leaves the Village with the Yellow and Red Loops but quickly takes a hard right turn to venture out into the woods alone. You will find yourself hoping over roots on a tight single-track that winds through a thick lush forest. Around mile 1 the terrain opens up to reveal old growth trees and the pine needle cushioned trail levels out enough to turn on the heat. At mile 1.5 the trail bends and overlooks an old rock quarry. At this point, if you’re not looking to take the triple-crown, and you wanted to hike out an additional ¼ mile to a bat cave, not THE bat, we highly recommend it. Another mile of steady climbing single-track brings you to some incredible views over the Ohio River and into Indiana. Don’t look too long or you’ll miss the sharp right turn on another single track to head back to the Village. Just before mile 3 you join with the red loop to take it home for a photo finish.

legs.name: Yellow Loop - Red Cedar Trail
legs.description: At a ¼ mile, the Yellow Loop veers left to split away from the other Loops to run alongside a perfect row of tall Red Cedars. Don’t like straight lines? You’ll love this one! A left turn places you on a twisting and turning, rocky and rooty single-track. Just as you start hitting your stride the trail drops 200 feet hits you in the gut and then drops again. Now the fun begins. From mile 3 to 3.5 the trail is a fun, tight single track that drops down into and then climbs back out of a ravine. And it keeps climbing and climbing all the way home to the Village.

legs.name: Red Loop - Otter Creek Trail
legs.description: The first two miles of the Red Loop are fast. The trail is soft with pine needles and snakes through dense Red Cedars. At mile 2 the views change and you quickly take the plunge to Lick Bottom…we couldn’t resist. At mile 3 things mellow out again as the trail turns to run along Otter Creek, the namesake of this Loop. The next 1.5 miles are fun. The trail hugs the crystal clear creek and passes over ledges and under rock outcroppings. We think it is the best section of the course. You can thank us later. Around mile 4.5 the trail leaves the creek and run along an old logging road. This is a good section to cruise and get your legs about you, because at mile 5.5 things will change. You will turn left onto a steep single-track and for about a quarter-mile your legs might be burning like a shot of Burbon.
